{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"913d2214-fcee-4330-85ff-d598560d1b11","content":"Update these three files:\n\n**1. `*.csproj`**\n```xml\n<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>\n```\n\n**2. `global.json`**\n```json\n{ \"sdk\": { \"version\": \"11.0.100\" } }\n```\n\n**3. `Dockerfile`**\n```dockerfile\nFROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/aspnet:11.0 AS base\nFROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:11.0 AS build\n```\n\nThen run `dotnet restore` to pick up any updated package versions. Check for any NuGet packages with a `10.0.*` version (e.g., `Microsoft.AspNetCore.*`, `Microsoft.Extensions.*`) and bump those to `11.0.*` as well.\n\n> **Note:** .NET 11 has not been released yet (current latest is .NET 9, with .NET 10 in preview). These version numbers follow the established naming convention, but you won't be able to build until the SDK and runtime are actually available.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0e4afc7d-904a-414e-aed3-72e8e2eaabb8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to update their .NET project from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a straightforward question I can answer from knowledge — no codebase to explore. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":320,"requestId":"B909:115126:1712922:1A1059E:69FD400C"},"id":"e0f3d6dd-960b-4012-b001-a390e9de8600","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:44:51.545Z","parentId":"79090e27-b8c8-4803-8216-2c789214c245"}
